# Frontend Standards

Apply to all frontend code in `app/**`, `components/**`, and `public/**`.

## Framework
- Use Next.js App Router (React 19).  
- Prefer Server Components by default; use Client Components only when necessary (`'use client'`).

## Routing & Data
- Follow `app/**` conventions for route handlers.  
- Avoid custom fetch wrappers inside components.  
- Push data fetching to Server Components or actions.

## Hooks
- Follow React’s rules of hooks.  
- Memoize expensive computations (`useMemo`, `useCallback`) sparingly, only when measurable performance benefits exist.

## Styling
- Use Tailwind v4 with configless mode.  
- Prefer utility classes; avoid ad-hoc inline styles unless dynamic.  
- Leverage shadcn UI patterns from `components/ui/*`.

## Components
- Keep components small and focused.  
- Co-locate tests under `__tests__`.  
- Reuse primitives (`components/ui/*`, `components/crypto/*`).

## Imports & Aliases
- Use `@/*` paths (`tsconfig.json`).  
- Group imports consistently: react/next, third-party, internal, styles/assets.

## State Management
- Prefer React state and server actions.  
- Do not introduce new global state libraries without explicit approval.

## Accessibility
- Enforce focus states, keyboard navigation, aria labels, and color contrast.  
- Use semantic HTML and `@testing-library` queries that reflect user behavior.

## Performance
- Avoid unnecessary client JS.  
- Lazy-load heavy components.  
- Use `next/image` (mocked in tests) and optimize assets in `public/`.

## Errors & Logging
- Do not `console.log` in shipped UI.  
- Show user-friendly error messages.  
- Log via backend (`src/lib/observability.ts`) if needed.

## Documentation
- Update `docs/*` and `README.md` when UX, routes, or component APIs change.
